  "text": "The Rust borrow checker analyzes MIR through a multi-stage pipeline in the rustc_borrowck crate:\n\n## 1. MIR Borrow Check Entry Point\nThe `mir_borrowck` function (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:117) is the query provider that initiates borrow checking for a function. It creates a BorrowCheckRootCtxt and calls `do_mir_borrowck()` to orchestrate the entire analysis.\n\n## 2. Borrow Set Construction\nBefore checking, a `BorrowSet` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs) is constructed by gathering all `Rvalue::Ref` expressions in the MIR. The `GatherBorrows` visitor (borrow_set.rs:242) collects borrows and identifies two-phase borrows through the `pending_activations` map. Each borrow receives a unique `BorrowIndex`.\n\n## 3. Two-Phase Borrow Resolution\nTwo-phase borrows are tracked through the `TwoPhaseActivation` enum (borrow_set.rs:66) with three states: `NotTwoPhase`, `NotActivated`, and `ActivatedAt(Location)`. The `insert_as_pending_if_two_phase` function (borrow_set.rs:341) marks mutable borrows as pending, and the `GatherBorrows::visit_local` method (borrow_set.rs:276) detects activation points when the temporary holding the borrow is used, transitioning the borrow state.\n\n## 4. Place Conflict Detection\nThe `borrow_conflicts_with_place` function (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:104) determines if two places (memory locations) conflict. It first checks if borrows and accesses are to the same local, then uses `place_components_conflict` (places_conflict.rs:131) to recursively compare projections element-by-element. The analysis returns `Overlap::Disjoint`, `Overlap::EqualOrDisjoint`, or `Overlap::Arbitrary` based on whether the places can potentially access overlapping memory.\n\n## 5. Dataflow-Based Borrow Tracking\nThe `Borrows` analysis in dataflow.rs (line 174) is a dataflow analysis that tracks which borrows are active at each program point. The `OutOfScopePrecomputer` (dataflow.rs:181) precomputes where each borrow goes out of scope by checking if the borrow's region does not contain that point, using the region inference context.\n\n## 6. Live Range Calculation\nRegion liveness is computed through `LivenessValues` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/values.rs:41), which uses a `SparseIntervalMatrix<RegionVid, PointIndex>` (values.rs:53) to represent which CFG locations each region is live. The `RegionInferenceContext` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/mod.rs:79) maintains `liveness_constraints` (mod.rs:90) that accumulate CFG points where regions must be live, computed from borrow data and control flow analysis.\n\n## Analysis Chain Flow\nThe analysis proceeds: (1) gather all borrows into BorrowSet, (2) identify two-phase activation points, (3) run dataflow analysis to track borrow activity, (4) compute region liveness constraints, (5) check place conflicts for each borrow-access pair using the conflict detection algorithm, and (6) propagate constraints through the region inference context to ensure soundness. This architecture enables non-lexical lifetimes (NLL) by deriving region bounds from the control-flow graph rather than lexical scope."
